---

## ğŸš€ Setup & Execution

### 1ï¸âƒ£ Create Project Folder

```bash
mkdir socket-demo
cd socket-demo
```

---

### 2ï¸âƒ£ Create Server File

```bash
nano DateServer.java
```

Paste:

```java
import java.net.*;
import java.io.*;

public class DateServer {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            ServerSocket sock = new ServerSocket(6013);
            System.out.println("Server started... Waiting for client");

            while (true) {
                Socket client = sock.accept();
                System.out.println("Client connected!");

                PrintWriter pout = new PrintWriter(client.getOutputStream(), true);
                pout.println(new java.util.Date().toString());

                client.close();
            }
        } catch (IOException ioe) {
            System.err.println(ioe);
        }
    }
}
```

Save: `CTRL + X â†’ Y â†’ Enter`

---

### 3ï¸âƒ£ Create Client File

```bash
nano DateClient.java
```

Paste:

```java
import java.net.*;
import java.io.*;

public class DateClient {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            Socket sock = new Socket("127.0.0.1", 6013);

            BufferedReader bin = new BufferedReader(
                    new InputStreamReader(sock.getInputStream()));

            String line;
            while ((line = bin.readLine()) != null) {
                System.out.println("Server Date: " + line);
            }

            sock.close();
        } catch (IOException ioe) {
            System.err.println(ioe);
        }
    }
}
```

---

### 4ï¸âƒ£ Compile Programs

```bash
javac DateServer.java
javac DateClient.java
```

---

### 5ï¸âƒ£ Run Server (Terminal 1)

```bash
java DateServer
```

Output:

```
Server started... Waiting for client
```

---

### 6ï¸âƒ£ Run Client (Terminal 2)

```bash
java DateClient
```

Output:

```
Server Date: Wed Feb 05 13:45:22 CST 2026
```

---

## ğŸŒ Simulating Different Devices on Same WiFi

Instead of using loopback (`127.0.0.1`), use your **real WiFi IP**.

### Get your IP address:

```bash
ipconfig getifaddr en0
```

Example output:

```
192.168.1.42
```

### Modify client:

```java
Socket sock = new Socket("192.168.1.42", 6013);
```

Recompile:

```bash
javac DateClient.java
```

Now the connection behaves as if itâ€™s between **two different devices** on the same network.

